stylometry: is used with probabilities and allows new info to be added into consideration with old information to form a new probability. it takes prior probablitlies and combines it with new information to create posterior probabilities. For exampe if we were trying to find the probability that the national market would produce a "great" market then we simply multiply a prior probabilitiy of have a great market by the probability of producing a great market through a test market also called the conditional market. We would also have to do this for both "fair" and "bad" markets. We then take the information at hand which we then can determine the best "great" market.
